  <section class="budget-section">
    <h2>What changed — you're building this yourself now</h2>
    <div class="verdict">
      <span class="verdict-tag">Update</span>
      <p><strong>The main cost is no longer money — it's your time and attention.</strong> With Claude Code doing the actual coding alongside you, the $2,000–$3,100 Fiverr estimate from before mostly goes away. What's left is small, predictable infra cost, plus a real time commitment from you to test, decide, and steer as it's built. Fiverr stays in your back pocket (your Option 2) for later — v1.1 features, or if you get stuck on something.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Cost</th><th>Amount</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="row-fit">
            <td>Supabase</td>
            <td class="cost">$0/mo</td>
            <td class="row-note">Free tier easily covers an MVP's worth of users, posts, and messages</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="row-fit">
            <td>Vercel hosting</td>
            <td class="cost">$0/mo</td>
            <td class="row-note">Free tier is fine until you have real, meaningful traffic</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Domain name</td>
            <td class="cost">~$12/yr</td>
            <td class="row-note">Optional for MVP testing — can launch on a Vercel subdomain first</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Your Claude Code plan</td>
            <td class="cost">already have it</td>
            <td class="row-note">This is genuinely the main "cost" now — it's what replaces the freelancer</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="recommend">
      <span class="label">Recommended move</span>
      Keep the ~$2,000–$3,100 you'd budgeted for Fiverr as a reserve, not a spend. Use it later for v1.1 (Projects board, group chat + AI, Team/Studio accounts) or to hire out anything you get genuinely stuck on — not as a starting assumption.
    </div>

    <div class="recommend warn" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <span class="label">Honest expectation</span>
      Claude Code writing the code doesn't mean zero effort on your side. You'll still need to run it, click through it, describe what looks wrong, and make product calls at each step. Budget real, regular time — a few focused sessions a week beats one long session, since you'll be learning the shape of the app as it comes together.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="setup-note-section">
    <h2>Before phase 0 — where you actually build this</h2>
    <div class="verdict">
      <span class="verdict-tag">Important</span>
      <p>This planning conversation isn't running inside your project. Open (or create) a dedicated project folder in VS Code — e.g. <strong>Documents\spotlight-enosis</strong> — and start Claude Code there. That folder, connected to your GitHub repo, is where the actual app gets built.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="timeline-section">
