    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="learn-section">
    <h2>What to learn — you're driving now, not just overseeing</h2>
    <div class="card-list">
      <div class="card-item">
        <span class="mark">→</span>
        <p>How to run the app locally (<code>npm run dev</code>) and actually click through it in your browser after each change.
          <span class="sub">This is your main feedback loop — don't just trust that code was written, look at it running.</span></p>
      </div>
      <div class="card-item">
        <span class="mark">→</span>
        <p>Git basics: commit and push, and commit often.
          <span class="sub">Every commit is an undo point. If Claude Code's next change breaks something, you can always go back.</span></p>
      </div>
      <div class="card-item">
        <span class="mark">→</span>
        <p>How to describe a problem without needing to fix it yourself — what you did, what you expected, what happened instead.
          <span class="sub">You're the tester, not the engineer. A clear description is enough.</span></p>
      </div>
      <div class="card-item">
        <span class="mark">→</span>
        <p>Roughly what each piece of the stack does: Next.js is what you see, Supabase is your data and logins, Vercel is where it lives online.
          <span class="sub">Enough to know which layer a problem is probably in when something goes wrong.</span></p>
      </div>
      <div class="card-item">
        <span class="mark">→</span>
        <p>Why secrets (API keys, database passwords) never get committed to GitHub, and how <code>.env</code> files keep them out.
          <span class="sub">A real security basic — a leaked key is a real-world problem, not a hypothetical one.</span></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="own-section">
    <h2>What you own</h2>
    <div class="card-list">
      <div class="card-item"><span class="mark">•</span><p>Domain name registrar account (when you get one)</p></div>
